y if I can use the same file for macro definitions. It seems that inline macro definitions might cause issues when they're in the same source file due to TASTy requirements. If encountering errors, there might be ways to avoid defining a new inline macro by using existing ones like `Literally`. I should also consider if a user-defined interpolator could help. It’s worth searching for existing tests with macros to clarify the implementation.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_xEepzG3zyU5uJ6OWP9VOCs5b|fc_02c7b9da1a15b1530169f6f6d344108194874437cdcc65d3de\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"rg -n \\\"scala\\\\.quoted|typeCheckErrors|inline def|\\\\$\\\\{\\\" tests/src -g '*.scala' | head -100\", \"timeout\": 10}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 12138, \"output\": 3037, \"cacheRead\": 11776, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 26951, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1777792682240, \"responseId\": \"resp_02c7b9da1a15b1530169f6f6aab0788194aa6b4589211d40cf\"}}\n2607:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Exploring Scala macros**\\n\\nI'm trying to understand how Scala 3 handles macro implementation, particularly if I can use the same file for macro definitions. It seems that inline macro definitions might cause issues when they're in the same source file due to TASTy requirements. If encountering errors, there might be ways to avoid defining a new inline macro by using existing ones like `Literally`. I should also consider if a user-defined interpolator could help. It’s worth searching for existing tests with macros to clarify the implementation.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_02c7b9da1a15b1530169f6f6ab43188194bdb7e3e3008e308f\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\