tial error in Scala 3 related to macros. It appears that I'm running into the \\\\\\\"Cannot call macro method\\\\\\\" issue. I want to verify if it's common and explore examples where macros are defined and called within the same file since that’s mentioned in the documentation. It seems that they don't clearly show the same file usage, but maybe it’s allowed since everything compiles together without a separate run. I suspect there are compiler staging requirements at play here.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering type checking issues**\\\\n\\\\nI'm looking into whether the build has the Scala 3 library version 3.3.6 and if typeCheckErrors are available. A potential issue could arise if the code snippet can't import the package object fixtures, given that it's type-checked at compile time. It seems that the type checking resolves already compiled dependencies, which could lead to failure if there are restrictions. I should also think about defining self-contained negative snippets to manage potential errors.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Reviewing testing approach**\\\\n\\\\nI’m considering using `compiletime.testing.typeCheckErrors` with the string \\\\\\\"nat\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"-1\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\" after importing `Literals.*`. Since tests are similar to `munit compileErrors`, they use the same compilation context imports. I'll need to verify if test assertions on the Error class are required, possibly using `.map(_.message)`. I sense a potential issue with the JUnit test method that includes `val invalidPortErrors = typeCheckErrors(...)`, as it might refer to a snippet that includes `nat`, a custom macro. I’ll stick to one test file and edit as needed.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_b2MAmP5TyVtRSWRxKN7Vmlxr|fc_02c7b9da1a15b1530169f6f6fc23a88194a3cb74a0987e3e6f\", \"name\": \"write\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/org.typelevel/literally_3/1.1.0/src/test/scala/org_typelevel/literally_3/Literally_3Test.scala\", \"content\": \"/*\\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\\n *\\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\\n */\\npackage org_typelevel.literally_3\\n\\nimport org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat\\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test\\nimport org.typelevel.literally.Literally\\n\\nimport scala.compiletime.testing.typeCheckErrors\\nimport scala.quoted.Expr\\nimport scala.quoted.Quotes\\n\\nfinal class Literally_3Test {\\n  import LiterallyTestFixtures.*\\n\\n  @Test\\n  def literalsGenerateDomainValuesAtCompileTime(): Unit = {\\n    val ephemeralPort = port\\\"49152\\\"\\n    val maximumPort = port\\\"65535\\\"\\n    val color = rgb\\\"#0a10FF\\\"\\n\\n    assertThat(ephemeralPort.value).isEqualTo(49152)\\n    assertThat(maximumPort.value).isEqualTo(65535)\\n    assertThat(color.red).isEqualTo(10)\\n    assertThat(color.green).isEqualTo(16)\\n    assertThat(color.blue).isEqualTo(255)\\n  }\\n\\n  @Test\\n  def validatorReceivesExactlyOneDecodedStringContextPart(): Unit = {\\n    val label = label\\\"service-A_42\\\\nblue\\\\tgreen\\\"\\n\\n    assertThat(label.value).isEqualTo(\\\"service-A_42\\\\nblue\\\\tgreen\\\")\\n  }\\n\\n  @Test\\n  def invalidLiteralsExposeValidatorErrorMessagesDuringTypeChecking(): Unit = {\\n    val nonNumericPortErrors = typeCheckErrors(\\\"\\\"\\\"\\n      import org_typelevel.literally_3.LiterallyTestFixtures.*\\n      port\\\"not-a-number\\\"\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\")\\n    val outOfRangePortErrors = typeCheckErrors(\\\"\\\"\\\"\\n      import org_typelevel.literally_3.LiterallyTestFixtures.*\\n      port\\\"70000\\\"\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\")\\n    val malformedColorErrors = typeCheckErrors(\\\"\\\"\\\"\\n      import org_typelevel.literally_3.LiterallyTestFixtures.*\\n      rgb\\\"#00xx00\\\"\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\")\\n\\n    assertThat(nonNumericPortErrors).isNotEmpty\\n    assertThat(nonNumericPortErrors.map(_.message).mkString(\\\"\\\\n\\\"))\\n      .contains(\\\"invalid port literal 'not-a-number'\\\")\\n      .contains(\\\"0 and 65535\\\")\\n    assertThat(outOfRangePortErrors).isNotEmpty\\n    assertThat(outOfRangePortErrors.map(_.message).mkString(\\\"\\\\n\\\"))\\n      .contains(\\\"invalid port literal '70000'\\\")\\n      .contains(\\\"0 and 65535\\\")\\n    assertThat(malformedColorErrors).isNotEmpty\\n    assertThat(malformedColorErrors.map(_.message).mkString(\\\"\\\\n\\\"))\\n      .contains(\\\"invalid RGB literal '#00xx00'\\\")\\n      .contains(\\\"#RRGGBB\\\")\\n  }\\n\\n  @Test\\n  def interpolationIsRejectedByLiterallyBeforeValidation(): Unit = {\\n    val interpolatedPortErrors = typeCheckErrors(\\\"\\\"\\\"\\n      import org_typelevel.literally_3.LiterallyTestFixtures.*\\n      val suffix = \\\"52\\\"\\n      port\\\"491$suffix\\\"\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\")\\n\\n    assertThat(interpolatedPortErrors).isNotEmpty\\n    assertThat(interpolatedPortErrors.map(_.message).mkString(\\\"\\\\n\\\"))\\n      .contains(\\\"interpolation not supported\\\")\\n  }\\n}\\n\\nobject LiterallyTestFixtures {\\n  final case class Port(value: Int)\\n\\n  final case class Label(value: String)\\n\\n  final case class RgbColor(red: Int, green: Int, blue: Int)\\n\\n  extension (inline context: StringContext)\\n    inline def port(inline args: Any*): Port = ${ PortLiteral('context, 'args) }\\n\\n    inline def label(inline args: Any*): Label = ${ LabelLiteral('context, 'args) }\\n\\n    inline def rgb(inline args: Any*): RgbColor = ${ RgbColorLiteral('context, 'args) }\\n\\n  private object PortLiteral extends Literally[Port] {\\n    override def validate(s: String)(using Quotes): Either[String, Expr[Port]] =\\n      s.toIntOption.filter(value => value >= 0 && value <= 65535) match\\n        case Some(value) => Right('{ Port(${ Expr(value) }) })\\n        case None => Left(s\\\"invalid port literal '$s': expected an integer between 0 and 65535\\\")\\n  }\\n\\n  private object LabelLiteral extends Literally[Label] {\\n    override def validate(s: String)(using Quotes): Either[String, Expr[Label]] =\\n      if s.nonEmpty && s.forall(isAllowedLabelCharacter) then Right('{ Label(${ Expr(s) }) })\\n      else Left(s\\\"invalid label literal '$s': expected letters, digits, hyphen, underscore, newline, or tab\\\")\\n  }\\n\\n  private object RgbColorLiteral extends Literally[RgbColor] {\\n    override def validate(s: String)(using Quotes): Either[String, Expr[RgbColor]] =\\n      parseRgb(s) match\\n        case Some((red, green, blue)) => Right('{ RgbColor(${ Expr(red) }, ${ Expr(green) }, ${ Expr(blue) }) })\\n        case None => Left(s\\\"invalid RGB literal '$s': expected #RRGGBB\\\")\\n  }\\n\\n  private def isAllowedLabelCharacter(character: Char): Boolean =\\n    character.isLetterOrDigit || character == '-' || character == '_' || character == '\\\\n' || character == '\\\\t'\\n\\n  private def parseRgb(s: String): Option[(Int, Int, Int)] =\\n    Option.when(s.length == 7 && s.head == '#' && s.tail.forall(isHexDigit)) {\\n      val red = Integer.parseInt(s.substring(1, 3), 16)\\n      val green = Integer.parseInt(s.substring(3, 5), 16)\\n      val blue = Integer.parseInt(s.substring(5, 7), 16)\\n      (red, green, blue)\\n    }\\n\\n  private def isHexDigit(character: Char): Boolean =\\n    character.isDigit || (character >= 'a' && character <= 'f') || (character >= 'A' && character <= 'F')\\n}\\n\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 961, \"output\": 2654, \"cacheRead\": 28672, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 32287, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1777792744061, \"responseId\": \"resp_02c7b9da1a15b1530169f6f6e8819881948740703df437ede4\"}, \"toolResults\": [{\"role\": \"toolResult\", \"toolCallId\": \"call_b2MAmP5TyVtRSWRxKN7Vmlxr|fc_02c7b9da1a15