ght('{ RgbColor(${ Expr(red) }, ${ Expr(green) }, ${ Expr(blue) }) })\\n+        case None => Left(s\\\"invalid RGB literal '$s': expected #RRGGBB\\\")\\n+  }\\n+\\n+  private def isAllowedLabelCharacter(character: Char): Boolean =\\n+    character.isLetterOrDigit || character == '-' || character == '_' || character == '\\\\n' || character == '\\\\t'\\n+\\n+  private def parseRgb(s: String): Option[(Int, Int, Int)] =\\n+    Option.when(s.length == 7 && s.head == '#' && s.tail.forall(isHexDigit)) {\\n+      val red = Integer.parseInt(s.substring(1, 3), 16)\\n+      val green = Integer.parseInt(s.substring(3, 5), 16)\\n+      val blue = Integer.parseInt(s.substring(5, 7), 16)\\n+      (red, green, blue)\\n+    }\\n+\\n+  private def isHexDigit(character: Char): Boolean =\\n+    character.isDigit || (character >= 'a' && character <= 'f') || (character >= 'A' && character <= 'F')\\n+}\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1777792797978}]}\n3594:[thinking] I need to finalize things concisely, but I should mention there was no run. First, I need to check for any top-level test class issues. Following the developer's rule, I see that coverage should be kept for each dynamic-access class. We only have one class, which is fine. There's this potential issue regarding public access for top-level test classes. I think I modified the necessary test file, which is good. However, I'm wondering if `scala.compiletime.testing.typeCheckErrors` requires the Scala 3 compiler, as it runs at compile-time. Also, the signature needs to return errors if the code doesn’t compile.\n3609:[assistant] - Validator-reported compile-time errors via `typeCheckErrors`.\n3614:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Evaluating test class issues**\\n\\nI need to finalize things concisely, but I should mention there was no run. First, I need to check for any top-level test class issues. Following the developer'